Fig. 1

Screenshot to show how EEBO returned the results of a keyword search for âexperimentalâ for the period 1663â64.

The first analysis was chronological: the hits were manually counted and classified by decade and where appropriate, in periods of significant change, in periods of 2 years. Obviously, the raw hit count needed to be normalized. This was crudely done by painstakingly adding up the occurrence in EEBO for every time period of words whose frequency Pumfrey assumed would not change over time but which were likely to appear in texts discussing experiment. These were âdivineâ, ânaturalâ and âet*â. 9

The chronological analysis confirmed as expected that English writers used the word âexperimentalâ long before it acquired the modern scientific sense present in the example of âexperimental philosophyâ. The first recorded use was in a religious context. In 1553, the first, posthumous edition of the âmartyrâ Sir Thomas Moreâs Dialoge of comfort against tribulacion mentioned the âlacke of such experimental taste as God geveth hereâ on earth of the pleasures waiting in heaven. 10

What was not expected was that meaning and uses of the word were overwhelmingly religious right up until the 1660s, and especially so during Englandâs Interregnum (1649â60). They described an âexperimental Christianityâ. An experimental Christian differed from the merely notional or formal Christian in that he knew Jesus experimentally, i.e. he could testify to a personal experience of the Holy Spirit dwelling in his heart. In order to plot the relationship between religious and scientific uses of the word it became necessary to classify the occurrences as religious or scientific, in effect to tag them semantically, as shown in Fig. 2 . Pumfrey did this, subjectively and manually, on the basis of the ten words of co-text and, where applicable, his knowledge of the book.
Fig. 2
